# EdLight News Page-by-Page Specification

## Purpose

This document translates the EdLight News website PRD into a practical page-by-page product specification that Copilot or a developer can build from directly.

The goal is to define:

* what pages exist
* what each page must do
* what sections each page should contain
* what content should appear in each section
* what interactions matter
* what should be prioritized in the MVP

This should help prevent the site from becoming a generic blog and instead make it feel like a real media product.

---

# 1. Global Product Rules

These rules apply across the entire website.

## 1.1 Global Experience Principles

* mobile-first layout
* premium editorial look
* fast-loading pages
* strong typography and hierarchy
* high-quality imagery
* clear category labeling
* easy scanning
* clean whitespace
* no cluttered sidebar-heavy layouts

## 1.2 Global Navigation

The primary navigation should include:

* Home
* Latest News
* Opportunities
* Haiti
* World
* Education
* Business & Economy
* Technology
* Explainers
* About

Optional later additions:

* Opinion / Insights
* Newsletter
* Search icon in header
* language switcher

## 1.3 Global Header

The header should include:

* EdLight News logo/wordmark
* main navigation
* search trigger
* mobile menu trigger on small screens

### Header Behavior

* sticky on scroll, but slim and unobtrusive
* should not take excessive vertical space on mobile
* should remain readable and elegant

## 1.4 Global Footer

Footer should include:

* EdLight News logo or wordmark
* short description of the platform
* key links
* About
* Editorial Standards
* Contact
* Privacy Policy
* Terms
* EdLight main site link
* social links

## 1.5 Global Content Card Rules

All story cards across the site should follow a consistent system.

Each card may include:

* image/thumbnail
* category label
* headline
* short summary or excerpt
* date/time
* optional tag or featured indicator

### Card Rules

* headline should be scannable
* excerpt should be short
* cards should not feel overdesigned
* hover states on desktop should feel subtle and premium
* spacing should remain clean on mobile

