# 3. Homepage Specification

## Page Goal

The homepage should immediately establish EdLight News as a living, modern, premium news platform. It should balance editorial credibility with fast discoverability.

## Primary User Jobs

* understand what EdLight News is
* see the biggest current stories
* quickly browse recent stories
* find opportunities
* discover featured or useful content
* continue deeper into the site

## Homepage Structure

### 3.1 Hero Section

This is the most important section on the homepage.

#### Purpose

* highlight top stories
* create a premium first impression
* communicate editorial quality instantly

#### Required Layout

* 1 dominant lead story
* 2 to 4 secondary stories beside or beneath it
* strong imagery
* category labels
* headline emphasis hierarchy

#### Content Rules

Lead story should include:

* large image
* category label
* strong headline
* short summary
* date/time

Secondary story cards should include:

* image or thumbnail
* category label
* headline
* optional date

#### UX Notes

* must feel dynamic, not like a generic blog list
* must not be overcrowded
* on mobile, lead story should come first and retain visual strength

---

### 3.2 Latest News Feed Preview

#### Purpose

Give users a quick way to see recent stories and move to the full Latest News page.

#### Required Content

* 4 to 8 recent story cards
* image
* category
* headline
* short excerpt
* publish date
* “View More” or “See All Latest” CTA

#### UX Notes

* should be easy to scan
* should feel current and alive
* date visibility matters here

---

### 3.3 Opportunities Spotlight

#### Purpose

Make opportunities a first-class content block on the homepage.

#### Required Content

* featured opportunity card
* 3 to 6 additional opportunity cards
* visible deadline
* opportunity type label
* short summary
* CTA to Opportunities Hub

#### UX Notes

* this section should feel visually distinct from standard news
* deadlines should be highly visible
* cards should feel practical and useful

---

### 3.4 Editor’s Picks / Featured Reads

#### Purpose

Promote evergreen explainers, strong features, or important stories that should keep getting attention.

#### Required Content

* 3 to 5 featured article cards
* clear section title
* visual consistency with overall card system

---

### 3.5 Category Highlights

#### Purpose

Help users navigate the site through key editorial pillars.

#### Suggested Categories

* Haiti
* Education
* Technology
* Business & Economy

#### Required Content

For each category block:

* section title
* top article
* 2 to 4 secondary headlines
* link to category page

#### UX Notes

* avoid making the homepage too long and repetitive
* category blocks should be selective, not exhaustive

---

### 3.6 Stay Updated Module

#### Purpose

Give users a way to stay connected.

#### MVP Option

* simple CTA to follow EdLight News on Instagram or visit EdLight pages

#### Later Option

* newsletter email capture

---

### 3.7 Footer Transition

The homepage should transition cleanly into the footer with enough whitespace and no abrupt ending.

---

# 4. Latest News Page Specification

## Page Goal

Provide a chronological or semi-curated stream of recent articles.

## Primary User Jobs

* browse the newest stories
* scan quickly by category
* access article pages efficiently

## Required Structure

### 4.1 Page Header

* title: Latest News
* short descriptor/subtitle

### 4.2 Content Feed

Each story listing should include:

* image
* category label
* headline
* short excerpt
* publish date/time

### 4.3 Pagination / Load More

MVP can use either:

* classic pagination
* load more button

Avoid infinite scroll at first if it complicates performance or UX.

### 4.4 Optional Filter Controls

Optional for near-term release:

* category filter
* date sorting

---

# 5. Category Page Specification

## Page Goal

Give each editorial category a strong destination page.

## Applicable Categories

* Haiti
* World
* Education
* Business & Economy
* Technology
* Explainers
* Opportunities (separate hub may be richer)

## Required Structure

### 5.1 Category Header

* category title
* optional one-line description
* optional visual accent tied to category

### 5.2 Featured Story Block

* one featured article with image and summary

### 5.3 Article Feed

* category-specific article cards
* headline, image, excerpt, date

### 5.4 Optional Tag/Subtopic Row

Possible future enhancement:

* elections
* scholarships
* AI
* careers
* higher education
* youth policy

### UX Notes

* category pages should feel curated, not empty
* they should look distinct enough to feel meaningful

---

# 6. Article Page Specification

## Page Goal

Deliver a premium reading experience that feels credible, modern, and easy to consume.

## Primary User Jobs

* read the story clearly
* understand why it matters
* trust the presentation
* move to related content

## Required Structure

### 6.1 Article Header

Must include:

* category label
* headline
* subheadline/dek if available
* byline or EdLight News attribution
* published date
* updated date if relevant
* hero image

### 6.2 Article Metadata Row

Can include:

* reading time (optional)
* author
* date
* share actions

### 6.3 Article Body

#### Requirements

* readable line length
* generous spacing
* high-contrast text
* paragraph rhythm that supports scanning
* support for subheadings
* support for bullet lists when appropriate
* support for inline links
* support for embedded images or quotes

#### Typography Rules

* should feel like a publication, not a note-taking app or blog builder template
* avoid overly narrow column on desktop
* avoid edge-to-edge text on mobile

### 6.4 Inline Opportunity / Related Block (Optional Contextual)

When relevant, allow insertion of:

* related opportunity card
* related explainer
* related article

This should be subtle and context-aware.

### 6.5 Article Footer Block

Must include:

* tags/topics
* related stories
* related opportunities where relevant
* previous/next story suggestion
* share actions

### 6.6 Sticky Elements

Use sparingly.
Avoid distracting sticky share bars or elements that cover content on mobile.

---

# 7. Opportunities Hub Specification

## Page Goal

Make opportunities easy to discover, scan, and act on.

## Primary User Jobs

* browse current opportunities
* filter by need
* find deadlines fast
* click into details

## Required Structure

### 7.1 Opportunities Hub Header

* title: Opportunities
* subtitle explaining what this section contains

### 7.2 Featured Opportunity Area

* one featured opportunity or deadline-sensitive item
* large card with deadline emphasis

### 7.3 Filter / Sort Bar

Recommended filters:

* opportunity type
* deadline
* region
* education level
* field/industry

MVP may start smaller with:

* type
* deadline status

### 7.4 Opportunity Grid/List

Each card should include:

* title
* type label
* deadline
* region/eligibility if relevant
* short summary
* CTA

### 7.5 Deadline UX

Deadline should be one of the most visually prominent fields.
Use clear formatting, such as:

* Closes April 30
* Deadline in 5 days
* Rolling applications

### 7.6 Empty State

If no opportunities match a filter:

* explain clearly
* suggest removing filters
* provide related recent items

---

# 8. Opportunity Detail Page Specification

## Page Goal

Help users quickly understand whether an opportunity is relevant and how to act on it.

## Required Structure

### 8.1 Opportunity Header

Must include:

* title
* type label
* deadline
* region/eligibility
* hero image or visual marker
* short summary

### 8.2 Key Information Panel

A high-utility section near the top containing:

* deadline
* eligibility
* location/region
* field
* cost/free if relevant
* official link / apply CTA

### 8.3 Main Body

Should include:

* overview
* who it is for
* benefits
* application steps
* notes/tips if relevant
* source/origin

### 8.4 CTA Block

Should clearly present:

* Apply Now / Visit Official Page
* Save deadline mentally through strong design emphasis

### 8.5 Related Opportunities

* 3 to 6 related listings

### UX Notes

* opportunity detail pages should feel more practical and action-oriented than news articles
* avoid burying essential information inside long text blocks

---

# 9. Search Results Page Specification

## Page Goal

Help users quickly find relevant articles and opportunities.

## Primary User Jobs

* search for a topic
* search for an opportunity
* filter results

## Required Structure

### 9.1 Search Header

* search input
* results count
* visible query text

### 9.2 Results Tabs or Labels

Recommended content distinction:

* All
* News
* Opportunities

MVP can also simply mix results with visible type labels.

### 9.3 Results List

Each result should include:

* content type label
* category or opportunity type
* headline/title
* excerpt
* date or deadline
* thumbnail when useful

### 9.4 Empty State

If no results:

* suggest another keyword
* suggest browsing categories or opportunities

---

# 10. About Page Specification

## Page Goal

Explain what EdLight News is and why it exists.

## Required Structure

### 10.1 Intro Section

* short mission statement
* what EdLight News covers

### 10.2 Why It Exists

* explain the platform’s focus on youth, Haiti, opportunities, and accessible information

### 10.3 Connection to EdLight

* explain relationship to the wider EdLight ecosystem without making the page overly promotional

### 10.4 What Readers Can Expect

* news
* explainers
* opportunities
* useful content

### 10.5 CTA

* explore latest news
* browse opportunities
* follow on social

---

# 11. Editorial Standards Page Specification

## Page Goal

Build trust and communicate seriousness.

## Required Structure

### 11.1 Editorial Principles

* accuracy
* clarity
* fairness
* usefulness
* responsibility

### 11.2 Content Standards

* how stories are selected
* how opportunities are shared
* correction/update approach
* sourcing philosophy

### 11.3 Tone and Presentation

* no sensationalism
* clarity first
* concise writing

### 11.4 Contact or Correction Channel

* how to reach EdLight News for corrections or concerns

This page does not need to be long, but it should feel real.

---

# 12. Contact Page Specification

## Page Goal

Provide a simple, professional way to reach the EdLight News team.

## Required Structure

* short intro
* contact email or form
* partnership / collaboration note if desired
* social links

Keep this page clean and low-friction.

---

# 13. 404 Page Specification

## Page Goal

Handle broken links gracefully while keeping users on the site.

## Required Structure

* clear message
* CTA to homepage
* CTA to latest news
* CTA to opportunities

Should feel on-brand, not default or forgotten.

---

# 14. Content Components Library

These reusable components should exist across pages.

## Required Components

* hero story card
* standard article card
* compact headline list item
* featured opportunity card
* standard opportunity card
* category label badge
* section heading row
* related story module
* search result item
* empty state block
* CTA block

A consistent component system will make the site feel much more premium.

---

# 15. Mobile Behavior Notes

## Mobile Priorities

* simplify hero layout without losing editorial feel
* collapse navigation cleanly
* maintain large enough tap targets
* keep article text readable
* make opportunities filters usable on small screens

## Do Not

* stack too many modules before the first useful story
* allow giant menus to feel clumsy
* let cards become cramped
* make article pages feel endless and dense without structure

---

# 16. Page Priority for MVP Build Order

## Recommended Build Sequence

1. global layout and navigation
2. homepage
3. article page
4. category page
5. opportunities hub
6. opportunity detail page
7. latest news page
8. search page
9. about + editorial standards + contact
10. 404 page

This order ensures the product’s core value is visible early.

---

# 17. Content Requirements for Launch

## Minimum Launch Content Recommendation

Before launch, aim to have at least:

* 12 to 20 news articles
* 8 to 15 opportunities
* 3 to 5 explainers or evergreen pieces
* complete About page
* complete Editorial Standards page

The site should not launch looking empty.

---

# 18. Final Guidance for Copilot / Build Team

When implementing this website:

* prioritize hierarchy over decoration
* prioritize scanability over cleverness
* prioritize strong content blocks over too many modules
* make opportunities feel like a core feature
* keep visual identity premium and consistent
* avoid generic blog defaults

The website should feel like the start of a serious media platform, not just a section on an organization’s site.
